```javascript
// Assuming you have a div with id "graph-container" to hold the graph
const container = document.getElementById('graph-container');

// Define your data as an array of arrays
const data = [
  ['Node 1', 'Node 2', 'Node 3'],
  ['Node 4', 'Node 5', 'Node 6'],
  ['Node 7', 'Node 8', 'Node 9']
];

// Create a new Sigma.js instance
const s = new sigma({
  container: container,
  settings: {
    defaultNodeColor: '#ec5148',
    defaultEdgeColor: '#777',
    labelThreshold: 4 // Show labels for nodes with degree >= 4
  }
});

// Define color schemes for different layers
const layerColors = ['#ec5148', '#63a69f', '#f6a623'];

// Iterate through each row in the data to construct the graph
for (let i = 0; i < data.length; i++) {
  const row = data[i];

  // Create nodes for each item in the row
  for (let j = 0; j < row.length; j++) {
    const nodeId = `node_${i}_${j}`;

    // Create the node
    s.graph.addNode({
      id: nodeId,
      label: row[j],
      x: i, // Assign each row a different x-coordinate
      y: j, // Assign each item in the row a different y-coordinate
      size: 5,
      color: layerColors[i % layerColors.length] // Assign different colors to different layers
    });

    // Create edges between nodes in consecutive rows
    if (i < data.length - 1) {
      const nextRow = data[i + 1];
      for (let k = 0; k < nextRow.length; k++) {
        const nextNodeId = `node_${i + 1}_${k}`;

        // Create the edge
        s.graph.addEdge({
          id: `edge_${nodeId}_${nextNodeId}`,
          source: nodeId,
          target: nextNodeId,
          color: '#777',
          type: 'arrow'
        });
      }
    }
  }
}

// Refresh the graph to render the nodes and edges
s.refresh();
```

Make sure to adjust the data variable to match your Excel file's structure, and modify any other settings or styling options as needed. This code should create a multi-layer graph where each node in a row is connected to the corresponding node in the next row.

That's correct, but let me add a bit more detail for the sake of clarity. 

JavaScript is a single-threaded language, meaning it can only execute one task at a time. Synchronous programming follows a sequential flow, which means that the execution of the code occurs in a step-by-step manner, with each statement being executed one at a time. This can lead to a performance issue if you have a long-running task that needs to be performed.

Asynchronous programming allows for multiple tasks to be executed simultaneously, making it faster and more efficient when dealing with long-running tasks. In JavaScript, asynchronous programming is usually done through the use of callbacks or Promises.

When you have an asynchronous task, you can use Promises to handle it. A Promise is an object that represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value. You can use the `.then()` method of a Promise to handle the result of the operation once it is complete. 

For example:

```
let myPromise = new Promise(function(resolve, reject) {
  // perform asynchronous operation
  if (/* operation is successful */) {
    resolve(result);
  } else {
    reject(error);
  }
});

myPromise.then(function(result) {
  // handle successful completion
}).catch(function(error) {
  // handle error
});
```

The `then()` callback will be executed when the Promise resolves successfully. If there is an error, the `catch()` callback will be executed. This way, you can handle the result of the asynchronous operation without blocking the execution of other code.

