Here's an example of how the rules might look like:

```
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /FutureMK/{document=**} {
      allow read: if true;
      allow write: if request.auth != null && get(/databases/$(database)/documents/users/$(request.auth.uid)).data.admin == true;
    }
  }
}
```

The `allow read: if true;` rule allows anyone to read the `FutureMK` collection, while the `allow write:` rule only allows authenticated users with the `admin` attribute set to `true` to write to the collection. 

Note that this assumes you have a `users` collection with documents corresponding to each user's UID. The `get(/databases/$(database)/documents/users/$(request.auth.uid)).data.admin == true` condition checks if the authenticated user's `admin` attribute is set to `true` in the corresponding document in the `users` collection. You'll need to adjust this based on your own use case.

Remember to also test your rules thoroughly to ensure they're secure and restrict access appropriately.

