service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /{document=**} {
      allow read; // allow all users and guests to read
			allow write: if request.auth.token.admin == true;
    }
  }
}

The security rule you have written allows all authenticated users to read any document in your Firebase Firestore database, and only users with an "admin" custom claim to write to any document.

This means that guests (unauthenticated users) are not allowed to read or write to any documents in your database, while authenticated users who are not admins can only read documents.

If you want to give more fine-grained control to your security rules, you can add additional rules that only allow certain users or groups to access certain documents or collections.

For example, you may want to create a separate collection for "Sale" documents and restrict access to this collection only to admins, like this:

```
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /Sale/{saleId} {
      allow read, create, update, delete: if request.auth.token.admin == true;
      allow get: if request.auth != null; // allow guests to view individual sale documents without editing
    }
    match /{document=**} {
      allow read, get; // allow all users and guests to read any document
      allow write: if request.auth.token.admin == true; // allow only admins to write to any document
    }
  }
}
```

In this example, we added a new rule that only allows admins to read, create, update, and delete documents in the "Sale" collection. This means that only admins can perform these actions on this specific collection, while allowing guests to view individual documents within the "Sale" collection without being able to modify them.

Remember to always test your security rules thoroughly to ensure they provide the necessary level of protection for your Firebase database.

