To reverse the values of two variables, you generally need to use a temporary third variable to hold the value of one of the variables during the swap process. Here's a basic example in different programming languages:

In Python:
```python
a = 5
b = 10

# Using a temporary variable
temp = a
a = b
b = temp

# Or, in Python, you can also do
a, b = b, a

print(a)  # Output will be 10
print(b)  # Output will be 5
```

In JavaScript:
```javascript
let a = 5;
let b = 10;

// Using a temporary variable
let temp = a;
a = b;
b = temp;

console.log(a);  // Output will be 10
console.log(b);  // Output will be 5
```

In Java:
```java
int a = 5;
int b = 10;

// Using a temporary variable
int temp = a;
a = b;
b = temp;

System.out.println(a);  // Output will be 10
System.out.println(b);  // Output will be 5
```

In C++:
```cpp
int a = 5;
int b = 10;

// Using a temporary variable
int temp = a;
a = b;
b = temp;

std::cout << a << std::endl;  // Output will be 10
std::cout << b << std::endl;  // Output will be 5
```

This is a basic operation that you can perform in almost any programming language. However, some languages offer additional ways to swap values without a temporary variable, such as the tuple unpacking feature in Python, which is shown in the Python example as an alternative method.

